<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-28T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-28T16:00:00-05:00" n="154" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.04418/93a: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Straus</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-28T16:00:00-05:00">December
                                    28, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>507. From time to time suggestions have been made by persons in
                            responsible positions, including members of Congress, with respect to
                            permanent neutrality legislation. Among such suggestions are the
                            following: <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>Embargo on all export trade to belligerents.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>Embargo on the export of all war materials such as oil, steel,
                                    iron and copper.</item>
                                <label>3.</label>
                                <item>Embargo on all articles in the last mentioned category in
                                    excess of the normal volume of shipments.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>Any comment you may possibly care to make regarding the desirability or
                            effect of the enactment of any of these three proposals would be
                            welcomed.</p>
                        <p>Please send copy to Embassies at London, Rome and Berlin and Legation at
                            Bern.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>